title: For Sale:  KSG 12 Guage
postcontent:
The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".
The pump includes an under picatinny rail mounted with a forward grip. It also has fold down sights on the top rail.  Also includes Forward and rear sling loops and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.
The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.
This gun is used in like new condition, comes with box, and added fore grip and sights.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Folding Stock + Extras for Ruger Mini-14 Wood/Steel
postcontent:
Vintage Mini 14 Underfolder by Federal Ordinance + Flash Hider + Peep Sight + Magazine + etc.

Years ago a "friend" "gave" me a stainless Mini-14 Ranch Model & I bought this stock for it.  Also bought a Williams Micrometer Peep rear sight and an M14-style flash hider.  Also an extended magazine & quite a lot of ammo.  Took it out once & ran a box of ammo through it.  Later he became an "Indian Giver" and took it back, but I kept my stock & upgrade parts & ammo.

I'm not that interested in Mini-14s anymore so it's unlikely I'll ever use these parts.  I'd rather *you* use them & convert them into something useful.

The stock is old, it's wood (seems to be Walnut) it's clean and the steel mechanism works perfectly.  As far as I can tell, I'm the only person who's mounted a rifle in it.  It fits the Ranch Model *perfectly*, so I'm sure it would also fit the "regular" Mini-14 receiver as well.
The stainless extended flash hider slips over the sights & pins into place.  I liked the way it looked.
Peep sights aren't for everybody, but I like them; and this Williams unit is a big upgrade over the factory sights!  Plus it's very precisely adjustable.
There's an extended magazine but I don't know how many rounds it holds.  Also a good bit of ammo.

From what I've been able to Google, the stock alone seems to be worth what I'm asking, and the flash hider and peep sight would add another $100 or so, nevermind the ammo and spare magazine.  I'd consider trading for a .308 Bolt Action rifle or a Lever Action (.44Mag or .30-30) for deer hunting (not a collectors piece and I don't even mind if it needs repairs).  Or make me a reasonable offer & I'll consider it.

I'd be willing to consider other interesting trades, so feel free to ask.  If I don't reply right away, please be patient.  When the stock is gone, this ad will go too.

No brag, but this all looked pretty awesome on a Stainless Steel Mini-14 Ranch Rifle, and with the stock folded it stows much better.

Can you give them all a Good Home?  I'm open to suggestions here, but no lowballers or tire kickers please.

title: For Sale:  Colt 1911a1 1947 commercial
location: St. Charles County, St. Louis, Missouri
postcontent:
Beautiful early 1947 Government Model s/n C222102. Pistol is all original with the Colt's mirror-bright factory finish rating about 99%. Difficult to find or to upgrade. Aside from the minor scratches/damage on the right side of the slide up front shown in photo, the finish is nearly flawless (no takedown scratch).  Front and rear grip straps are absolutely beautiful.  A nice addition to any Colt collection. This pistol is one of the last beautiful, hand-polished post-WWII chemically blued pistols. By about mid-1947, Colt's went to the non-glare matte blue finish on all but the flats of the slide and frame. This pistol is entirely high-polish, except for the top of the slide, rear of the slide, top sides of the grip tang radius that meet up to the rear of the slide done to provide a matched mating finish, see photo 4), and the top of the hammer.  The first post-WWII Colt Govt. Models came off the line in late 1946. The earliest pistols used surplus military parts leftover from WWII, until supplies were depleted. This pistol has a long 1911 checkered trigger. Other parts that MAY be surplus WWII military are: receiver, sights, magazine release, slide stop, hammer, thumb safety, grip safety, recoil spring, recoil spring guide, recoil spring plug, barrel bushing and various small internals. These parts were identical in the WWII pistols and the first post-WWII commercials. I know of no way to tell them apart. This slide  has the earliest post-WWII markings "COLT'S PT. F.A. MFG. CO. HARTFORD, CT. U.S.A." on the left side and COLT (beside) AUTOMATIC (over) CALIBRE .45 on the right side. These slide markings were only used in the first part of 1947, because Colt's changed their name to Colt's Manufacturing Company in early 1947...and changed their slide markings to reflect this. Perfectly struck VP and factory inspector 5  marked on left side of trigger guard. Perfectly struck factory assembler 4 mark on right side of trigger guard. GOVERNMENT MODEL (over) C222102 on right side of receiver. All markings perfectly struck to indicate original Colt's factory finish. No markings on top of the receiver by the disconnector, which is correct according to Clawson. Bright bullet feed ramp on receiver.  The barrel appears to be original to the pistol and is military P proofed on the left lug. Top of the chamber is Colt's factory prepared with the bright, unfinished surface there and on the crown of the muzzle. Bore is bright and flawless.
Email for more detailed photos. If you're the buyer, check it out upon receipt. If not fully satisfied that the pistol is original and correct, simply return for full refund within the 3-day, non-firing inspection period for a refund. ***Have the pistol checked and verified by a competent gunsmith prior to firing.*** Valid C&R or FFL required.*** Not sold where prohibited by law.
